    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Cuba Embargo: Desired Results?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ralph C Whaley letter on Sen Jesse Helms's June 24 article agrees with his support for United States embargo of Cuba but holds trade with China also supports dictatorship and should be banned</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Jesse Helms is right (''On Trade, Cuba Is Not China,'' Op-Ed, June 24). Trade with Communist Cuba only supports the dictatorship. It prolongs the slave status of the Cubans.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Jesse Helms is right (''On Trade, Cuba Is Not China,'' Op-Ed, June 24). Trade with Communist Cuba only supports the dictatorship. It prolongs the slave status of the Cubans.</p>
        <p>But China is no different. Trade with China supports the dictatorship and prevents freedom for the slaves in China. United States policy should be the prohibition of all trade with every tyranny, Communist or fascist, religious or secular.</p>
        <p>RALPH C. WHALEY  Barron, Wis., June 24, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
